AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: hello ser  datatokens are erc20  a datanft (erc721) has its own did and ddo. within the ddo you can define one  or more than one  services. each service has itâ€™s own dt.  example  letâ€™s imagine you want to sell a javascript course. these are 2 examples of how you could ocean dts:  example 1 the course is called javascript  and has 3 tiers. this course will be represented as a datanft with its own did/ddo. in the ddo  you add 3 services to represent each tier  each of which will be represented by its own datatoken.  javascript course (erc721) javascript basics for beginners (dt1 for free) javascript intermediate (dt2 @ usdc 100) javascript full course (dt3 @ usdc 299) (edited)  example 2 alternatively  each tier can also be represented as a datanft and have its own did/ddo with only one service:  javascript basics for beginners (erc721) dt1 for free javascript intermediate (erc721) dt1 @ usdc 100 javascript full course (erc721) dt1 @ usdc 299  each service can be customised quite flexibly to have a different price  expiry date  whitelist and more

CONTENT: @databites.eth curious about your idea and wondering if you are wanting experimenters to download you data set or just run algo's on it ? either scenario would require adjusted settings when you publish the dataset to the market

AUTHOR: white_rider_
CONTENT: hello @databites.eth  let me try to respond to your questions:  option 1 - if you choose to publish a dataset as downloadable  interested buyers can acquire datatokens to gain access to it. the data provider ensures privacy by encrypting the source details such as the url or ipfs id. however  buyers can download the data. when users purchase access through datatokens  they essentially obtain a license to use the data for a specific purpose set by the data provider and enforced by smart contracts. nevertheless  tracking and monitoring if they share or use the data differently from its intended purpose can be challenging due to the decentralized nature of the system.  option 2 - anyone can develop algorithms to process your dataset. to facilitate this  it's crucial to include sufficient information in the dataset documentation  allowing users to understand its structure without directly accessing the raw data. best practices involve providing a sample file that demonstrates the data's format. however  to prevent potential data theft or misuse  the data publisher must approve algorithms before they are allowed to run on the dataset. this approval process helps ensure that only trustworthy and non-malicious algorithms can access and process the data  safeguarding its integrity and security.   i hope this clears up any confusion you may have.

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: greetings  everyone. thank you for spending your valuable time to read my feedback on the ambasador program. please take all criticism and sense for common sense purposes to improve the ocean protocol ecosystem and optimize all processes.    first of all  as an ambassador i am very happy to be in such a community and thank you all for your input. but  now to get to the point of this post:  huge thanks to @blockchainlugano for the work done. this effort to introduce something new has really succeeded and the ambassador program has been transformed. but in all new innovations there are also disadvantages:  1) lack of tracking the work of other ambassadors (in a good way) i every person who is sensible analyzes some things. so while writing some content  i had difficulties in analyzing the topics that others wrote on so that there was no overlap.   2) binding your wallet to the platform. as you have seen in the community  many do not have the desire to connect their wallet to an unknown source. this does not prevent us from creating another wallet and using an "empty" one  but security is paramount!!!!  3) incorrect distribution of responsibilities. i don't have information on internal operational aspects within the team. but it seems to me that almost most of the work is done only by @blockchainlugano  in ambassador programm. maybe i'm wrong and underestimate other people's labor (but i'm judging purely from my own view).   4) i propose to reformat the ambassador program next week. all ambassadors will write treads on one given topic and whoever dives deeper and hits the most important aspects is the opf winner.

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: 5) new ambasadors have rose-colored glasses. with the upgrade of the ambasador program  there is a very large influx of users. this is good on both sides. but i'd like to only touch on the bad one: these people came here for money  which is not just handed out here. i do not want to strongly affect other people's personalities and suggest to reduce the number of ambassadors to a minimum (the most active) and make a decent pay (by the standards of the project).    perhaps i forgot to mention something in the moment of writing this post. but there is no growth without mistakes. and ocean protocol clearly has room to grow. all the best and all the best.

AUTHOR: captainfeci
CONTENT: hello everyone how can i join this ambassador program

AUTHOR: blockchainlugano
CONTENT: hiya  thanks for writing this and taking the time out to do so. it is super constructive and what the program aims for  which is being a community where everyone has a voice and contributes to its betterment.  as per #1 i have created a solution to this in a new document (link in ambassador channel and pinned) allowing everyone to post their work so that anyone can see what another has submitted.  let me know if you feel this works.  as per #2  part of us wanting to reward contribution that we worked hard on with rep3 is for your work to go with you. everything created has value  and we think it only fair that via your wallet address (of your choice) you should have a 'resume'  otherwise there is no good way to verify your contributions in a decentralized manner. if the wallet address receives mocean as payment  with polygon gas fees  there is nothing stopping you from transferring to another wallet for security.  as per #4 we cannot give out a topic  this is up to the ambassadors  we sometimes give guidelines if a new aspect of opf has launched  but we prefer to leave the imagination open. many past threads came out of nowhere  stuff even we hadn't thought of. the winner (s) is simply chosen by opf. it's not  the best of the bunch wins (what if its all subpar?)  but rather  the quality of writing and topic most valued by opf to retweet.  as per #5  not everyone joining in will become ambassadors nor want to  they may want to simply feel part of a community and participate in simpler bounties. the onboarding process changed since you came in  and trust me  it is not so easy.  hope that makes sense. we can continue this convo in the ambassador channel for others to weigh in.

CONTENT: hey   there! thanks for reaching out and desire to explore more about ocean protocol!   > ocean protocol supports multiple programming languages >  > javascript: ocean.js is a javascript library used for interacting with the ocean protocol ecosystem. > python: ocean.py is a python library used for integrating applications with the ocean protocol ecosystem.   > i think the above mentioned technologies have already captured most of the market. i think that in the next year will evolve - crm ai systems will find sales opportunities  automate customer capture  predict demand  make product recommendations and guide the customer through the next steps to purchase.  > ocean protocol launched the ocean token in november 2017  alongside its marketplace framework which outlines the market attributes and components necessary to deploy the decentralized ocean protocol data exchange. >  > as i remember correctly at launch ocean protocol has hard cap â€”  hard caps by each phase â€” seed  pre-launch and network launch  > ocean token model: > ocean is designed to increase with a rise in usage volume  > - a rise in usage volume â†’ leads to more network revenue  which goes to ocean community via (a) burning ocean (b) other community initiatives > - a rise in usage volume â†’ leads to more ocean being locked  > ocean is actually deflationary as 5% of all network revenue is burned. this means ocean supply will decrease faster with greater adoption of the ocean protocol.   > ocean protocol foundation - webpage to explore core of team - https://oceanprotocol.com/about-us/foundation#:~:text=founders%20of%20ocean%20protocol as%20entrepreneurs%2c%20designers%20and%20technologists.

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: a consensus mechanism is a method used in blockchain networks to ensure that all participants in the network agree on the state of the ledger or the validity of transactions. consensus mechanisms are designed to prevent fraud  double-spending  and other types of malicious activity on the network.  in the context of ocean protocol  the consensus mechanism used is proof of stake (pos)  also  for your analysis  i recommend looking into our documentation at https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/. it is equipped with ai that can help you with almost any question. just enter your question in the search bar  and the documentation will find an answer for you)

CONTENT: the majority of newly minted tokens are programmed to go towards data farming following a btc-like vesting curve. the contracts proving the release & vesting are open-source and can always be monitored at:    https://github.com/oceanprotocol/vw-cli/blob/main/contracts/vestingwallethalving.sol https://github.com/oceanprotocol/vw-cli/blob/main/contracts/vestingwalletlinear.sol  to have one less point of failure in the system. ocean's vision has always been to slowly (but responsibly) move to a fully decentralised architecture  with ideally zero points of failure to make ocean fully censorship resistant.    however  this comes in little steps. and as the technology becomes more mature/robust  the more smart contract automation will be taking place. and more keys will be thrown away (hence also the multi-sig).    this is what further enhance security and will eventually make ocean fully community-owned  just like bitcoin. no owners  but its community!    does this clarify?

CONTENT: hi  i am quite confused. my active rewards are much lower than expected this week. i received more in active rewards last week despite the apy of the dataset i allocated being lower. so i have a greater apy this week but less in rewards?

AUTHOR: xanxus_18559
CONTENT: i did:(

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: hello xanxus!)  the amount of active rewards you receive can vary due to several factors beyond just the apy of the dataset you allocated to. here are some potential reasons for the discrepancy:  1. changes in data consume volume (dcv): if the dcv for the dataset you allocated to has decreased  this could result in lower rewards despite a higher apy. 2. changes in veocean allocations: if other participants have allocated more veocean to the same dataset  the rewards could be distributed among more stakeholders  reducing your share. 3. changes in the total ocean locked: if there has been an increase in the total ocean locked  it could affect the distribution of rewards. 4. variations in the ocean reward schedule: the total amount of ocean distributed as rewards can change  as outlined in the reward schedule. 5. timing of allocations: the timing of when you allocate your veocean can influence the rewards due to the progressive counting of voting power throughout the week.

AUTHOR: dhlegit
CONTENT: hi all  i have to questions about ocean and the working of veocean.  (1) i understand by locking ocean in veocean  i could get rewards from data farming. but what exactly does veocean if i not delegate my veocean to datasets? what i mean is: by locking to veocean is it simply giving the marketplace liquidity or?  and my second question is: (2). you read a lot of times about partnerships with ocean or companys who make there own marketplace from ocean's code. does i as a investor in ocean benefit from those marketplaces? does there marketplaces use ocean tokens to run? or what is the benefit from company's who work with the by ocean created marketplace 'layout'?

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: hello oceaners ğŸŒŠ.   icymi: in less than 3 months after launching the ocean predictoor has reached new milestones  reaching an impressive $1 million dollars with 500% growth and 2 million transactions (80% growth) ğŸ˜   and this is just the early stages  there are many more thrilling updates awaiting us in 2024 ğŸš€.   our latest achievements tell a lot  and you can ride the wave too - https://predictoor.ai  you will find the rest of the amazing deets here in this tweet by ocean founder trent mcconaghy  link https://twitter.com/trentmc0/status/1742705296655757503?t=2a6jjr9r1i-xfmfjt6bg-q&s=19

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: hello dh! 1. by locking ocean to get veocean  you are not simply providing liquidity to the marketplace. veocean serves several purposes:  passive ocean rewards: holding veocean entitles you to passive ocean rewards every week.  active ocean rewards: allocating veocean towards data assets can earn you active ocean rewards weekly  based on the sales of the assets you support in the ocean ecosystem.  delegating: you have the option to delegate your veocean to other data farmers who can curate datasets for you  potentially earning you apy on active rewards.  publisher stake bonus: if you are a publisher  allocating veocean to your own asset gives your veocean a 2x bonus  incentivizing publishers to engage with their assets and benefit the ocean ecosystem.  locking ocean for veocean is a commitment that aligns with the long-term incentives of the ocean protocol ecosystem. it is not just about providing liquidity but also about participating in the governance and curation within the ocean protocol's data economy.

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: 2. when companies create their own marketplaces using ocean's code  the ocean ecosystem can benefit in several ways. while these third-party marketplaces may use a different currency for transactions  if they are publicly accessible  indexable  and abide by the fee structure set out by ocean protocol  transaction fees would be remitted back to the ocean community. these fees contribute to the ecosystem's revenue  which can support the buy-and-burn process of the ocean token  potentially reducing the supply and creating value for ocean holders.  additionally  the usage of ocean's open-source tech stack  even if transactions are paid in a currency other than ocean  still generates a small fee for the ocean community with each consumed transaction. this fee accrues whether ocean is used or not  and the details are provided in the documentation. you can read more here: https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/developers/contracts/fees

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: i hope this proves helpful to you. if you have any questions  feel free to ask)

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: 2.1 when marketplaces are publicly accessible  indexable  and abide by the fee structure set out by ocean protocol  it means that these third-party marketplaces  like gaia-x  bdp  and acentrik  are using ocean components and are open for public use. they are also searchable and follow the fee guidelines established by ocean protocol. if they meet these conditions  transaction fees from these marketplaces will be remitted back to the ocean community.

CONTENT: currently  you can explore our data farming or ocean predictoor.  ocean data farming (df) is an incentive program by ocean protocol that rewards participants with ocean tokens for engaging in activities that boost data consume volume (dcv) within the ecosystem. participants can earn rewards by locking ocean into veocean  curating data  or making predictions. df operates similarly to defi liquidity mining but is specifically tailored for dcv.  ocean predictoor is both a stack and a dapp designed for prediction feeds with accountability for accuracy through staking. it is globally distributed and resistant to censorship as it operates on-chain  and its accuracy is expected to improve over time due to its incentive structure. the initial use case for ocean predictoor is predicting defi token performance.

CONTENT: hi all! what is the point to delegate to a dataset. i understand you can get rewards. but what are my veoceans tokens doing when i delegate them? is it liquidity for the data set?

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: hello @dh! how are you?)  when you delegate your veocean tokens to a dataset in volume data farming (volume df)  you are not providing liquidity but rather allocating your veocean to data assets with high data consume volume (dcv). this is a form of data curation  as your veocean allocation helps to signal the value of the data asset within the ocean protocol ecosystem. the more veocean allocated to an asset  the higher its rank in terms of dcv  which can influence the distribution of ocean rewards from the volume df.

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: fees are turned to 0 in certain contexts within the ocean protocol ecosystem to provide flexibility and incentivize participation.   for instance  there are currently no charges for publishing fees when you publish an asset on the ocean marketplace.   additionally  the provider  publisher market  and consume market fees can be set to 0 and are customizable in the market configuration.   this approach allows marketplace owners to tailor their marketplaces to their specific needs and preferences without mandatory fees  potentially lowering the barrier to entry and encouraging more users to participate in the ecosystem.

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: how predictions work with ocean?  predictions work with ocean through the ocean predictoor  which is a stack and dapp for prediction feeds with accountability for accuracy via staking. predictoors submit individual predictions and stake on them  earning money when they're correct and losing money when not. this incentivizes accurate prediction feeds. predictoor is built on the ocean protocol stack and uses the oasis sapphire privacy-preserving evm chain for keeping predictions private unless paid for.  1. the number of predictoor bots behind the usd-btc 1h prediction is not disclosed to prevent potential exploitation and manipulation. the platform aims to show only trustable and secure metrics  2. you cannot directly invest in a specific predictoor bot. instead  you can become a predictoor yourself by running your own prediction bot and staking ocean tokens on your predictions. if your predictions are accurate  you earn a portion of the sales revenue and potentially receive slashed stakes from incorrect predictions.

CONTENT: i also recommend reading an article on how to earn as a predictoor.   https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/predictoor/pdr-earn

AUTHOR: dhlegit
CONTENT: thanks for the explanation. how does wrong predictors impact the predictions if i buy the btc prediction?

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: if the prediction is wrong  the staked amount on that wrong prediction is going to be slashed and distributed among people who submitted the right predictions. this mechanism ensures that only accurate predictors are incentivized  which in turn impacts the quality of the predictions you buy. the more ocean people stake on their predictions  the more confidence you can have in the prediction  as it reflects their willingness to risk their stake on being correct.

AUTHOR: ndubss
CONTENT: bridging ocean tokens from bnb chain to ethereum requires using a bridge platform. luckily  there are several reputable options available for this specific task. here's how you can do it:   1. choose a bridge platform:  binance bridge: this is the official bridge supported by binance. it's a convenient choice if you already use binance and it offers competitive fees. however  be aware of potential network congestion on both chains. anyswap: another popular option offering fast bridging and various supported chains  including bnb chain and ethereum. consider their fees and potential liquidity for larger amounts. portal bridge: a new bridge focused on interoperability  offering quick transactions and competitive fees. do your research on its track record and community feedback before proceeding.  2. connect your wallet:   connect your wallet containing the ocean tokens on bnb chain to the chosen bridge platform. most bridges support popular wallets like metamask  trust wallet  and binance chain wallet.   3. select tokens and amount:   choose ocean as the token you want to bridge and specify the amount you want to transfer. remember to check the minimum transfer amount and any network fees involved.   4. initiate the bridge transaction:   review the transaction details and confirm the bridge process. depending on the platform  you might need to approve additional steps within your wallet.   5. wait for completion:   the bridging process can take some time depending on network congestion. the platform should provide you with an estimated completion time and transaction tracking information.   6. claim your tokens on ethereum:   once the bridge completes  your ocean tokens will be available on your chosen ethereum address. connect your wallet to the bridge platform or any ethereum wallet connected to the same address to access your bridged tokens.

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: predictoor continues to delight us with its capabilities!   for those unfamiliar  predictoor is a stack and dapp for prediction feeds that ensures accuracy through staking. it's globally distributed  censorship-resistant  and built on the ocean protocol stack.  to get started with predictoor  follow these steps:  begin by exploring the dapp at predictoor.ai.  click on "run bots" and review the predictoor or trader readme. the "how to earn" section of the blog provides detailed information.  for predictoors  if your prediction is correct  you earn money  but if it's wrong  your staked amount is slashed and distributed among those who made the correct predictions. while it's technically possible to predict without using bots  doing so manually for hundreds or thousands of submissions would be tedious and error-prone. therefore  using a bot is the most practical approach.  for traders  the confidence in a prediction can be assessed by the amount of ocean staked on it. the accuracy of predictoor predictions over time depends on various factors  including historical price information and potentially other data sources like social media or news.

AUTHOR: hebbianloop
CONTENT: hi  i just realized i never introduced myself! i'm shady  a phd in neuroscience and founder of opscientia. my efforts have been dedicated to building a de-sci (decentralized science) utilizing all of the benefits of web 3.0 to accelerate the pace of scientific innovation through peer-to-peer storage of massive datasets  confidential cloud computing  and sharing through data marketplaces. our mission is to help transform the process of scientific discovery to include citizen scientists working together in parallel with traditional academia.

AUTHOR: mantisclone
CONTENT: i want to expand upon my initial introduction:  my name is david hunt-mateo and i'm a software engineer with 7 years of professional experience. for the last three years  i developed a cross-platform  on-device  noise-robust speech recognition library. users liked it because it would work on whatever hardware they had  it never transmitted their audio to the cloud  and it would work in harsh environments like the middle of the ocean or a noise manufacturing floor. unfortunately  i was laid off at the end of 2020. soon after  i began reading about blockchain and was immediately enthralled by the benefits that decentralized web 3 technologies could bring. i am currently participating in the kernel block 2 fellowship program hosted by gitcoin.   i've spent 4 weeks researching to understand the web 3 landscape and to determine exactly what use cases excited me most. i determined that i am most passionate about the user's right to privacy and data ownership  especially regarding ai and communication. having developed a production ai system myself  i'm familiar with the massive amounts of data required as well as the difficulties small companies face when trying to acquire data. furthermore  it's not hard to recognize the tactics that larger companies employ to extract data from their users. i think the ocean protocol could provide a solution to these problems  and furthermore  that it is poised for massive growth as the mainstream consciousness becomes aware of the abuse it's suffered at the hands of big tech.   as such  the ocean protocol tops the list of projects i'd like to become involved with. my career has meandered through several industries and many layers of the technology stack. i consider myself a jack of many trades  adept at learning/applying new technologies  and a skilled communicator. my specialties in the past have been cross-platform development  desktop and native android apps  and embedded software.

AUTHOR: ssskylark
CONTENT: what sets ocean apart is  simply allows data sales without losing control over the ip on the data - this is especially useful for machine learning/ai tasks. the algorithms can train a model on data without the data leaving the owners premesis. this enables data usage that was not possible before e.g. for medical data.  additionally it also enables the creation of datatokens and liquidity pools for datasets which allow for price discovery  curation and reputation of datasets. high quality datasets will have different setups of their datatokens than unsuccessful ones.

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: you should try https://oceanacademy.io - this gives a good introduction to ocean protocol. in ocean protocol the data is not stored on the blockchain but the governance is organised via the blockchain. so the data resides on premise and the access to the data by algorithms is organised via compute-to-data. this means that the data is not going to leave the data storage and that the data owner (you) can allow algorithms to access the data or not.

AUTHOR: rikrapmund
CONTENT: hi everyone! my name is rik rapmund  supporter of ocean since the ico and founder of workpi: an hr tech startup that predicts the required skills for rapidly evolving jobs in organisations to reduce skill gaps and eliminate mismatches. besides workpi we are also building work x: a decentralized platform economy for work where service providers and customers can work together without intermediaries.   because we believe that the personal data of our users should be owned and controlled by themselves  we are working together with the european commission on a self-sovereign identity solution (ssi). users will be able to connect their career related data such as assessments  diplomas  certificates or references to their digital passport/identity. this is also where ocean comes along. it's a great thing to give data back to the people  but is also comes with a challenge: how do we learn from it when the data is scattered around the world? the technology of ocean is very promising to solve this problem. to this end we introduce *compute-to-ssi*. learn more about our proposal here: https://port.oceanprotocol.com/t/workpi-oceandao-round-9/862  we're very interested to get to know the community and hear your feedback!   cheers!   rik

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: hey!  we're glad to see you here in the ocean protocol communityğŸ˜ğŸŒŠ  to start learning about ocean protocol and its role in creating a decentralized data marketplace  you can follow these steps:  understand ocean protocol's mission and core technologies: ocean protocol aims to level the playing field for ai and data by enabling the monetization of ai models and data while preserving privacy. its core technologies include data nfts & datatokens for token-gated access control and compute-to-data for buying and selling private data while preserving privacy.  explore what you can do with ocean: depending on your interest or expertise  you can engage with ocean protocol in various capacities such as a builder  data scientist  or ocean holder. each role offers different opportunities  from building token-gated ai dapps and apis to earning rewards through data farming.  join the ocean protocol community: becoming an ocean ambassador is a great way to get involved. you can join ocean protocol's discord server  participate in discussions  and apply to become an ambassador through the #treasure-hunter channel on discord.  learn through doing: consider participating in data challenges hosted by ocean protocol to apply your skills in real-world problems and earn prizes.  dive deeper into documentation: visit the developers and data scientists pages on ocean protocol's website for step-by-step instructions  apis  libraries  and other tools to build dapps or integrate with the ocean ecosystem.  stay informed: keep up with the latest updates and resources by following ocean protocol's official channels and participating in community events.  https://oceanprotocol.com/  https://market.oceanprotocol.com/

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: and if you want you can try data farming  data farming https://df.oceandao.org/  is ocean's incentive program that rewards ocean to participants who lock ocean into veocean  curate data  or make predictions. it aims to drive data consume volume (dcv) and is similar to defi liquidity mining but tailored for dcv.

CONTENT: i hope it helps you ğŸ™‚ if you have any further questions  feel free to ask

CONTENT: it kinda has a lot of flaws for now because i was lazy ğŸ™‚ . i started creating embeddings for the docs ( split the md if needed ) and push them in pinecone (vector database) . after this i got a little crazy and i did this for most of our repos (not just md   everything ğŸ¤£  ) so sometimes it gives crazy results

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: the plan is to improve the docs and some of the readmes and then just do embeddings for those

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: we use gpt 3.5-turbo   so the flow is   get prompt -> create embedding for it -> get top x results from pinecone - > format it and feed it to gpt

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: i started with remembering last 5 messages from the user  this worked kinda bad because once it gives you a bad result it sticks to it and whatever you ask in the future it will give you constant bad answers

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: so no chat history for now

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: @robin | dataunion hope this answered your question . i didn't try fine tuning because that works only with davinci  curie   babbage and ada. and also it's way more work to create the training data. but if i have time i'll give that a shot as well. also in this case i would probably stick with curie at best because davinci is way more expensive.
